<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Written evidence submitted by IntierraRMG (UK)</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:20pt">EIS 08</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by IntierraRMG (UK)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The contribution below (in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">bold</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">) is made on behalf of IntierraRMG (UK), a mining database provider, whose head office is in Perth, Australia.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">1. What is the contribution to the UK economy of extractive industries in the UK?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Although the direct contributi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">on to the economy from the domestic extractive industry is low, there is a significant contribution from related sectors (see below).</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">2. How does the UK-based extractive industr</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">y</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> support employment:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">a) In the UK, and </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">b) For UK citizens overseas?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">This </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">emp</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">loyment </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">support </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">(both within and external to the UK) </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">stems, largely, from the UK's historic mining prowess. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Because of its once-large extractive industry, t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">he region has a well-developed mining equipment and service sector, which now supplies the internati</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">onal industry.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">3. Does UK industry benefit more widely from the UK’s position as a centre for extractive industries</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">eg i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">n sales of machinery and services to international businesses in the sector?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Yes, clearly. Manufacturers in the UK design, make and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">despatch equipment for the international mining industry, and there are myriad organisations in the UK that can be expected to benefit from this activity. These include the importers and fabricators of metal, transport companies, external (local) consultan</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">ts on design and construction, and banks/brokers that finance the work. Non-mining UK industries will also benefit from the additional earnings and expertise of the mining-related companies and their staff. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Being an acknowledged centre of excellence will </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">also attract visits by overseas mining companies, whose executives are likely to visit other associated industries while in the UK (eg the London Stock Exchange, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">London Metal Exchange, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">staff recruitment firms, risk assessors, security and logistics advisor</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">s, mining engineering firms and metals traders).</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">4. Has the boom in London-listed extractive companies with businesses overseas over the last two decades resulted in a strengthening in the UK’s competitive position in this sector?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">There is no clear direct evidence of a stronger competitive position. However, the improved strength in related sectors (finance, law and risk assessment) is likely to have made </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">a positive</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> indirect </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">impact.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> For example, the UK accounted for almost 22% of th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">e finance raised globally for mining in the quarter to end-June. This </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">made</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">the London Stock Exchange third only to the Toronto Stock Exchange and the Australia Stock Exchange.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">5. What are the corporate governance concerns raised by the number of extract</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ive industries companies listed in the UK? Are there reputational risks for the UK and UK financial institutions in being a centre for such businesses?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">There have been </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">serious </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">corporate-governance issues at several mining companies listed in the UK with op</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">erations overseas</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">, and there is certainly a risk to the UK's </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">repu</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">tation. This seems likely, however, to be kept under control.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">6. Is there sufficient engagement between UK extractive industries and the NGO sector? Are there examples of best practice in en</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">gagement between the extractive industries and NGOs?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">There is plenty of engagement between the two sectors, not least through the International Council of Metals and Mining. Nevertheless, more interaction is still required.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">7. Does the UK have the skills </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">base to remain a centre for the extractive i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ndustries and to ensure that UK-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">based businesses benefit from potential future opportunities such as shale gas?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Yes, there is still a good-enough skills base. This is particularly strong in the finance and legal </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">sectors, and there is perhaps concern that the engineering skills might start to wither without a strong domestic extractive industry.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">8. What is the impact of the industry of the UK signing up to the EITI?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Very positive, in that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">the requirements of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">EITI </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">are essential to maintaining </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">reputational risk, which is still </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">core </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">strength </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">of UK</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> businesses</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">9. Would </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">increased regulation for London-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">listed extractive companies result in competition from elsewhere</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> or can it be used to make the UK a centre of excell</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ence for best practice and corporate governance?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">There is no choice in this matter. UK businesses are highly regarded for their competence and reliability. Increased regulation might increase short-term competition but it is probably essential to maintain </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">good practice (especially with so-many overseas companies coming to the UK for finance and advice).</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">10. What is the competitive landscape for the extractive</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> industries in the 21st Century, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">and is it in the UK’s interest to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> remain a global centre</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Competit</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">ion will increase with regard to the UK's supply of equipment and services, so domestic companies must focus on the quality and reliability of their offerings. This will be made easier if the UK (and London in particular) is able to maintain its role as a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">global centre of excellence.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Regards</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Dr Chris Hinde</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">E</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ditorial D</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">irector</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">September 20th, 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>